narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: This course improved my ability to close-read poetry, understand the ways in which Romantic poets inspire and affect one another, discuss poetry with others, and write analytical essays.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: This course covers a breadth of Romantic poetry and draws on some fantastic works. Unfortunately, we often did not discuss a majority of the poems we had read for a given seminar, and I wish we had more time to do so. Additionally, it would be helpful if student's could receive more feedback on their essays -- particularly regarding how grades were formulated.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes I would. I have taken a lot of English classes at Yale, and Romanticism as a concept gets thrown around a lot. This class, more than any I've taken, has finally helped me get a real grasp of what that movement meant, especially to the poets who were writing during it. If you are wanting to take this class because you want to read the niche Romantic poets, that isn't what is focused on. You start with Blake, then Wordsworth and Coleridge, then Shelley and Byron. The poet focused on the most is definitely Wordsworth, and his influence will appear throughout the class and other poets. So if you want to learn more about Wordsworth, especially "The Prelude," then this class might be good for you.
Yes! Professor Brisman is truly so passionate about Romanticism and the contents of the course, it was such a treat to learn from him.
I would recommend this course to any student passionate about poetry and eager to discuss it in a group.
